  "distance": "307.471 km (191.054 miles)",
  "event_preview": "Suzuka International Racing Course measures 5.807 km (3.608 mi) and features 18 turns in its unique figure-of-eight layout - the only one of its kind on the Formula 1 calendar - in Suzuka, Mie Prefecture, Japan. The circuit hosts the 2025 Japanese Grand Prix as Round 3 of the season. Designed as a Honda test track by Dutchman John Hugenholtz in 1962, Suzuka made its Formula 1 debut in 1987 and has been a fixture on the calendar ever since, renowned for its relentless sequence of high-speed challenges: the snaking Esses in Sector 1, the Degner curves, the sweeping Spoon, the flat-out commitment required at 130R, and the Casio Triangle chicane onto the main straight. The circuit runs counterclockwise and features three DRS zones. The official race lap record stands at 1:33.282, set by Max Verstappen for Red Bull during the 2023 Japanese Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Sebastian Vettel, who clocked 1:27.064 for Ferrari in Q3 of the 2019 weekend.",
